name: still way too long, and I'll explain to you why:

Despite what some of the articles have turned into, the SCP Foundation reports aren't meant to be an exhaustive breakdown of the item's entire history: it's a report that gives you the very basics on what to expect when you encounter the item. For instance: note that 173 says nothing about the item's origin, where it is located, prior casualties, etc. It just tells you what exactly you need to know if you need to work with this item and survive.

I read 342 and notice that the entire first paragraph could be summed up in one sentence: "SCP 342 can be safely stored in a locked file folder, as it poses no danger as long as it is not actively used.

The concept is good enough that I'm going to spend the time to do some major liposuction and tear out the majority of the redundant information: I hope you're not offended by this, and that you'll see me as an editor who is simply trying to make this the best article it can be. :)





